value.value: A traumatic injury to the head.
Pain in various parts of the head, not confined to the area of distribution of any nerve.
Hearing loss resulting from disorders of the central nervous system auditory pathways.
A condition in which a person loses the ability to hear high frequency sounds.  It is typically associated with impairment of the inner ear.
A condition in which a person loses the ability to hear due to exposure to high intensity sound.
An electrocardiographic finding of blocked cardiac electrical impulses along the fibers normally responsible for impulse conduction.
An anatomical defect of a gross structure of the heart.
Tearing of the heart muscle.
Tearing of the heart muscle as a sequela of acute myocardial infarction.
A T-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma arising from the skin. Representative examples include mycosis fungoides and primary cutaneous anaplastic large cell lymphoma.
Abdominal discomfort with retrosternal pain usually associated with gastroesophageal reflux.
Osteophytes that most commonly develop on the distal interphalangeal joints, often in the setting of osteoarthritis.
Intracellular red blood cell inclusions comprised of denatured hemoglobin.
A congenital malformation characterized by the partial or total absence of the distal half of a limb.
An autosomal recessive hemoglobinopathy with a mild clinical course. Most patients are asymptomatic. When symptoms appear, they include mild hemolytic anemia and occasionally jaundice.

A hemoglobinopathy that is considered a hybrid of sickle cell disease and hemoglobin C disease. Patients present with the symptoms of sickle cell disease but the latter are less frequent and severe compared to sickle cell disease.
A laboratory test result which indicates free hemoglobin in the urine.

label.value: Hemoglobinuria due to Hemolysis from External Causes

value.value: Hemoglobin in the urine that is due to hemolysis from an external cause.

label.value: Mature T-Cell and NK-Cell Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma

value.value: This type of lymphoma is not frequently seen in the western hemisphere. Clinically, with the exception of anaplastic large cell lymphoma, mature T- and NK-cell lymphomas are among the most aggressive of all hematopoietic neoplasms. Representative disease entities include mycosis fungoides, angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma, hepatosplenic T-cell lymphoma, and anaplastic large cell lymphoma.
Bleeding into the peritoneal cavity that is not associated with physical trauma.
Bleeding originating from the rectal wall and anus.
A tick borne hemorrhagic fever resulting from infection by Nairovirus.
A serious condition caused by Dengue virus infection. Patients present with an acute febrile illness followed by restlessness, irritability, and bleeding. It may lead to hemorrhagic shock and death.
Inflammation of the liver resulting from ingestion of alcohol.
The protrusion of part of an organ or fibroadipose tissue through an abnormal opening.

label.value: Hernia without Mention of Obstruction or Gangrene

value.value: The protrusion of an organ, or the fascia of an organ, through the wall of the cavity that normally contains it, without mention of obstruction or necrosis of the herniated contents.

A congenital or acquired weakness or opening in the diaphragm which allows abdominal contents to protrude into the chest cavity; congenital diaphragmatic hernias are caused when the embryonic diaphragm fails to fuse.
The protrusion of abdominal cavity contents into the thoracic cavity via a hole in the diaphragm, which was acquired via a traumatic etiology.
The protrusion of contents of the abdominal cavity, into the weak area at the posterior wall of the femoral canal, just inferior to the inguinal ligament.

A superficial fibromatosis arising from the soft tissue of the palm. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts, and an infiltrative growth pattern. It predominantly affects adult males.
The protrusion of a sac-like structure containing fibroadipose tissue through an abnormal opening in the inguinal region.
A protrusion of the abdominal cavity contents into the inguinal canal through the superficial inguinal ring.
A protrusion of the abdominal cavity contents into the inguinal canal through the deep and superficial inguinal rings.
The protrusion of abdominal cavity contents into the scrotal sac.
Physical and psychological dependence on the drug heroin.
A lesion caused by type 1 or type 2 herpes simplex virus, involving the oralfacial region.
A form of herpes zoster infection characterized by dermatitis of the skin of the eyelid due to reactivation of latent virus associated with the ophthalmic branch of the trigeminal nerve.
Infection of the vulva and the vagina caused by herpes simplex virus.
A congenital or traumatic abnormality in which the femoral head slips out of the acetabulum.
A sensation of discomfort emanating from the pelvis, its supporting structures, or its articulation with the femur (acetabulofemoral or femoroacetabular joint).

Any chemical, biological or physical agents that increase the risk of neoplasms in humans or animals.  Carcinogens include natural or synthesized compounds, certain viruses, and various sources of radiation.  A carcinogen may directly alter the genetic material of cells (genotoxic), thereby initiating or promoting the process of malignant transformation; it also may induce cancers by mechanisms that do not involve a direct alteration of cellular genetic material (non-genotoxic). (NCI04)

A localized or generalized inflammatory skin disorder characterized by the formation of papules and ring-shaped plaques in the skin. Morphologically these lesions are granulomatous inflammatory processes with central necrosis surrounded by palisading histiocytes.

A congenital disorder characterized by the absence of myenteric ganglion cells in the distal colon. It results in a functional stenosis of the distal colon and a massive distention of the proximal colon.
An infection that is caused by hookworms.
Abnormally increased pain sense.
An inheritable form of hyperlipidemia, in which there are excess lipids in the blood.
A laboratory test result indicating abnormally high concentrations of gamma globulins in the blood.
Increased motor activity that is not goal directed.
Elevated levels of lipids in the blood.
